      <h2 id="editorial-heading" class="visually-hidden">USD to RMB guide</h2>

      <article id="what-is-rmb">
        <h3>What is RMB?</h3>
        <p>
          RMB, short for Renminbi (meaning "the people's currency"), is the official currency of the People's
          Republic of China. The yuan (CNY) is its primary unit, similar to how the dollar is the unit of the
          US currency system. You'll often see "RMB" and "yuan" used interchangeably in everyday conversation
          and on <a href="/#converter">currency converters</a>, and for practical purposes when converting <strong>USD to RMB</strong>
          they refer to the same value. The Renminbi is issued by the People's Bank of China (PBOC), which also
          manages the currency's trading band against the US dollar and other major currencies.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article id="usd-vs-rmb">
        <h3>USD vs RMB Explained</h3>
        <p>
          The US dollar floats freely on global markets, with its value set by supply and demand across banks,
          funds, and central banks worldwide. The RMB, by contrast, trades within a managed band set daily by
          the PBOC, which allows some movement around a reference rate but intervenes to prevent extreme swings.
          This difference matters for anyone tracking <strong>USD to RMB exchange rate</strong> movements: the
          yuan tends to move more gradually than fully floating currencies, and sharp single-day changes are
          less common. Both currencies remain central to global trade, with the dollar as the world's primary
          reserve currency and the RMB playing a growing role in China's trade settlements.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article id="factors">
        <h3>Factors Affecting Exchange Rates</h3>
        <p>Several forces move the USD/CNY pair, and the same forces broadly apply to other pairs like USD/PKR or USD/MXN:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Interest rate differentials</strong> — when the US Federal Reserve holds rates higher than the PBOC, dollar-denominated assets often become more attractive.</li>
          <li><strong>Trade balances</strong> — a country running a large trade surplus tends to see steadier demand for its currency.</li>
          <li><strong>Capital flows</strong> — foreign investment into or out of a country shifts currency demand.</li>
          <li><strong>Central bank policy</strong> — direct intervention, reserve requirements, and reference-rate settings all shape short-term moves.</li>
          <li><strong>Geopolitical and macro events</strong> — trade disputes, elections, and global risk sentiment can trigger rapid repricing.</li>
        </ul>
      </article>

      <article id="history">
        <h3>Historical USD to RMB Trends</h3>
        <p>
          Since China's 1994 currency reform unified its dual exchange-rate system, the yuan has moved through
          several distinct phases: a peg near 8.28 per dollar through the early 2000s, a decade of gradual,
          managed appreciation toward roughly 6.1 per dollar by 2014, and a more recent period of two-way
          volatility that has generally kept the pair between about 6.3 and 7.3 yuan per dollar. The
          <a href="/#rates">trend chart above</a> gives a simplified illustrative view — for exact historical
          data, financial data providers publish full daily series going back decades.
        </p>
      </article>

